# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The **1934 FIFA World Cup** was the 2nd edition of the FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial international football championship for senior men's national teams.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] It took place in Italy from 27 May to 10 June 1934.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The 1934 World Cup was the first in which teams had to qualify to take part.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Thirty-two nations entered the competition; sixteen teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Reigning champions Uruguay boycotted the tournament as only four European teams had accepted their invitation to the 1930 tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Italy beat Czechoslovakia 2–1 to become the second World Cup champions and the first European winners.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The 1934 World Cup was marred by being a high-profile instance of a sporting event being used for overt political gain.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In particular, Benito Mussolini was keen to use this World Cup as a means of promoting fascism.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The Federale 102 ball, which was manufactured in Italy, was the match ball provided for the 1934 World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] After a lengthy decision-making process in which FIFA's executive committee met eight times, Italy was chosen as the host nation at a meeting in Stockholm on 9 October 1932.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The decision was taken by the executive committee without a ballot of members.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The Italian bid was chosen in preference to one from Sweden; the Italian government assigned a budget of Lire 3.5 million to the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] For the first time, teams had to play qualifying matches to enter the competition: 32 countries applied to enter the finals tournament, of which 16 qualified.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Even so, there were several notable absentees.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Reigning World Cup holders Uruguay declined to participate, in protest at the refusal of several European countries to travel to South America for the previous World Cup, which Uruguay had hosted in 1930.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] As a result, the 1934 World Cup is the only one in which the reigning champions did not participate.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The British Home Nations, in a period of self-imposed exile from FIFA, also refused to participate, even though FIFA had offered England and Scotland direct entry to the tournament without qualification.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Despite their role as hosts, Italy were still required to qualify, the only time the host needed to do so.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The qualifying matches were arranged on a geographical basis.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Withdrawals by Chile and Peru meant that Argentina and Brazil qualified without playing a single match.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Twelve of the sixteen places were allocated to Europe, three to the Americas, and one to Africa or Asia (including Turkey).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Only 10 of the 32 entrants, and 4 of the 16 qualified teams (Brazil, Argentina, United States, and Egypt, the first African team to qualify for a World Cup finals tournament), were from outside Europe.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The last place in the finals was contested between the United States and Mexico only three days before the start of the tournament in a one-off match in Rome, which the United States won.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Ten of these teams made their first World Cup appearance.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] This included 9 of the 12 European teams (Italy, Germany, Spain, the Netherlands, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, Sweden, Austria, and Switzerland) as well as Egypt.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Egypt was the first team from Africa in the finals and did not qualify again until the next time the competition was held in Italy, in 1990.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The number of supporters travelling from other countries was higher than at any previous football tournament, including 7,000 from the Netherlands and 10,000 each from Austria and Switzerland.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The group stage used in the first World Cup was discarded in favour of a straight knockout tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] If a match was tied after ninety minutes, then thirty minutes of extra time were played.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] If the score was still tied after extra time, the match was replayed the next day.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The eight seeded teams – Argentina, Brazil, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Austria, Czechoslovakia and Hungary – were kept apart in the first round.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] All eight first-round matches kicked off at the same time.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Hosts and favourites Italy won handsomely, defeating the USA 7–1; *The New York Times* correspondent wrote that "only the fine goal-tending of Julius Hjulian of Chicago kept the score as low as it was".
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Internal disputes meant Argentina's squad for the tournament did not contain a single member of the team which had reached the final in 1930.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In the end, *La Albiceleste* would partake with an amateur squad.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Against Sweden in Bologna, Argentina twice took the lead, but two goals by Sven Jonasson and a winner by Knut Kroon gave Sweden a 3–2 victory.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Fellow South Americans Brazil also suffered an early exit.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Spain beat them comfortably, with 3–1 as the final score.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] For the only time in World Cup history, the last eight consisted entirely of European teams – Austria, Czechoslovakia, Germany, Hungary, Italy, Spain, Sweden, and Switzerland.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] All four non-European teams who made the journey to Italy were eliminated after one match.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In the quarterfinals, the first replayed match in World Cup history took place, when Italy and Spain drew 1–1 after extra time.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Italy won the replay 1–0; their play so physical that at least three Spaniards had to depart the field with injuries.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Italy then went on to beat Austria in the semifinals by the same score.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Meanwhile, Czechoslovakia secured their place in the final by beating Germany 3–1.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The Stadium of the National Fascist Party was the venue for the final.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] With 80 minutes played, the Czechoslovaks led 1–0.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] The Italians managed to score before the final whistle and then added another goal in extra time to be crowned World Cup winners.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Over the years, several sources have reported that the tournament was marred by bribery and corruption and could have been influenced by Italian dictator Benito Mussolini, who used it as a propaganda tool for fascism.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] According to these accusations, Mussolini personally selected referees for the matches where the Italy national team were playing, while the Italian government meddled in FIFA's organisation of events, reorganising the logistics of the matches to further promote fascism.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] Later commentary has described Italy's successful defence of the following World Cup in France in 1938 as an opportunity to counter the allegations surrounding the 1934 tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1934 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] With five goals, Oldřich Nejedlý was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In total, 70 goals were scored by 45 players, with none of them credited as an own goal.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1934-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition (not counting replay results).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The **1938 FIFA World Cup** was the 3rd edition of the World Cup, the quadrennial international football championship for senior men's national teams.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] It was held in France from 4 to 19 June 1938.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Italy defended its title in the final, beating Hungary 4–2.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Italy's 1934 and 1938 teams hold the distinction of being the only men's national team to win the World Cup multiple times under the same coach, Vittorio Pozzo.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] It was the last World Cup for 12 years as the 1942 and 1946 World Cups were cancelled by World War II.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] France was chosen as host nation by FIFA in Berlin on 13 August 1936.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] France was chosen over Argentina and Germany in the first round of voting.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The decision to hold a second consecutive tournament in Europe (after Italy in 1934) caused outrage in South America, where it was believed that the venue should alternate between the two continents.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] This was the last World Cup to be staged before the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Because of the decision to hold a second successive World Cup in Europe, many teams from the Americas did not join the competition or withdrew after an initial application.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Most of the South American teams, including Uruguay and Argentina, declined to take part in the competition after the controversy of the Peru v Austria match at the Football tournament of the 1936 Summer Olympics.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The United States and Mexico joined the qualifying rounds but eventually withdrew.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Argentina submitted a late application (which was accepted), before a definitive withdrawal due to disagreements between the National Federation and the local clubs.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Spain meanwhile could not participate because of the ongoing Spanish Civil War.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] It was the first time that the hosts, France, and the title holders, Italy, qualified automatically.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Title holders were given an automatic entry into the World Cup from 1938 until 2002.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Of the 14 remaining places, eleven were allocated to Europe, two to the Americas, and one to Asia.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] As a result, only three non-European nations took part: Brazil, Cuba (making their debut) and Dutch East Indies (now Indonesia, also making their debut), the latter being the first Asian country to participate in a FIFA World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] This is the smallest ever number of teams from outside the host continent to compete at a FIFA World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Austria qualified for the World Cup, but after qualification was complete, the Anschluss united Austria with Germany.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Austria subsequently did not take part in the tournament, with some Austrian players joining the German squad, although not including Austrian star player Matthias Sindelar, who refused to play for the unified team.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Austria's place remained empty and Sweden, which would have been Austria's initial opponent, progressed directly to the second round by default.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Other teams to make their World Cup debuts included Poland and Norway.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams originally qualified for the final tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] However, 15 teams participated after Austria's withdrawal due to the Anschluss.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] As of 2026, this was the only time Cuba and Indonesia (formerly Dutch East Indies) qualified for a FIFA World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The knockout format from 1934 was retained.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] If a match was tied after 90 minutes, then 30 minutes of extra time were played.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] If the score was still tied after extra time, the match would be replayed.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] This was the last World Cup tournament that used a straight knockout format.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The draw was staged in Paris on 5 March 1938.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] As the qualifying process was still ongoing, many paper slips reported the names of two teams, which were both in competition to qualify.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The FIFA committee identified eight seeded teams, irrespective of their current qualification.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The seeded teams were: Argentina, Austria, Brazil, Czechoslovakia, France, Germany, Hungary and Italy, so six European teams and two South-American.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] On 15 March 1938, Austria was invaded by Nazi Germany and the Austria national team withdrew.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Argentina withdrew from the tournament after disagreements between the clubs and the National Federations so two of the original seeded teams did not take part in the final competition.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Sweden was given a bye when Austria withdrew.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Five of the seven first round matches required extra time to break the deadlock; two games still went to a replay.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] In one replay, Cuba advanced to the next round at the expense of Romania.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] In the other replay, Germany, which had led 1–0 in the first game against Switzerland, led 2–0 but eventually was beaten 2–4.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Sweden advanced directly to the quarterfinals as a result of Austria's withdrawal, and they proceeded to beat Cuba 8–0.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The hosts, France, were beaten by the holders, Italy, and Switzerland were seen off by Hungary.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Czechoslovakia took Brazil to extra time in a notoriously feisty match in Bordeaux before succumbing in a replay; the South Americans proved too strong for the depleted Czechoslovak side (both Oldřich Nejedlý and František Plánička had suffered broken bones in the first game) and won 2–1.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] This was the last match to be replayed in a World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Hungary convincingly beat Sweden in one of the semifinals 5–1, while Italy and Brazil had the first of their many important World Cup clashes in the other.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The Brazilians were without their star player Leônidas, who was injured, and the Italians won 2–1.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Brazil topped Sweden 4–2 for third place.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Rumour has it, before the finals Benito Mussolini was to have sent a telegram to the team, saying "Vincere o morire!" (literally translated as "Win or die!").
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] This should not have been meant as a literal threat, but instead just an encouragement to win.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] However, no record remains of such a telegram, and World Cup player Pietro Rava said, when interviewed in 2001, "No, no, no, that's not true.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The final itself took place at the Stade Olympique de Colombes in Paris.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Vittorio Pozzo's Italian side took the lead early, but Hungary equalised within two minutes.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] The Italians took the lead again shortly after, and by the end of the first half were leading the Hungarians 3–1.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Hungary never really got back into the game.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] With the final score favouring the Italians 4–2, Italy became the first team to successfully defend the title and were once more crowned World Cup winners.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Because of World War II, the World Cup was not held for next 12 years, until 1950.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] As a result, Italy were the reigning World Cup holders for a record 16 years, from 1934 to 1950.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Ottorino Barassi, hid the trophy in a shoe-box under his bed throughout the Second World War and thus saved it from falling into the hands of occupying troops.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] Eleven venues in ten cities were planned to host the tournament; of these, all hosted matches except the Stade de Gerland in Lyon, which did not host because of Austria's withdrawal.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1938 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] With seven goals, Leônidas was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] In total, 84 goals were scored by 42 players, with two of them credited as own goals.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1938-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The **1970 Women's World Cup** (Italian: **Coppa del Mondo**; sponsored name **Martini & Rossi Cup**) was an association football tournament organised by the Federation of Independent European Female Football (FIEFF) in Italy in July 1970.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] It featured women's teams from seven countries and is the first known tournament to be named as a women's football World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Matches were played in Genoa, Bologna, Milan, Bari, Salerno, Naples, and the third-place playoff and final were both in Turin.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was won by Denmark, represented by Boldklubben Femina.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Eight teams were scheduled to appear in the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The first list of participants, published in February 1970, consisted of Argentina, Denmark, France, Italy, Brazil, Czechoslovakia, England, and the Soviet Union.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] This was changed in a later revision, with West Germany, Mexico, Austria and Switzerland replacing Argentina, France, Brazil and the Soviet Union in May 1970.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Czechoslovakia would have been the only country from Europe's Eastern Bloc to compete, but the team withdrew because of visa issues.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The crowds for the tournament were "30,000-strong".
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Denmark won the tournament after beating Italy 2–0 in the final.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Teams were divided into the "northern" group (in Genoa, Bologna and Milan), and "southern" (Bari, Salerno, Naples) with the top teams meeting in the final.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The tournament did not involve FIFA, which had held the first men's World Cup in 1930 but did not hold any women's event until 1988.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The host country's matches are considered official by the Italian Football Federation.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The Italian women's league had been established in 1968.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Mexico, a losing semi-finalist 2–1 to Italy, were described as the "revelation" of the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] Tournament memorabilia was collected at an exhibition in Pessione di Chieri (Turin) from June to August 2019.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1970-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was followed by the 1971 Women's World Cup in Mexico, and the series of five Mundialito tournaments from 1981 to 1988 in Japan and Italy, before the 1988 FIFA Women's Invitation Tournament and 1991 FIFA Women's World Cup, both in China.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The **1971 Women's World Cup** (Spanish: **1971 Campeonato de Fútbol Femenil**) was an association football tournament for women's national teams organised by the Federation of Independent European Female Football (FIEFF) in Mexico in August–September 1971.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Held in Mexico City and Guadalajara, it is the second known tournament to be named as a women's football World Cup after the 1970 edition in Italy and the first time in the same place after the men's 1970 FIFA World Cup tournament in the previous year.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] It was held twenty years before the first official FIFA women's world cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The tournament featured six national teams from Latin America and Europe, including hosts Mexico which qualified automatically.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Denmark were the tournament champions, defending its title by winning the final 3–0 against Mexico, in front of a 110,000 crowd.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] A women's football international match was played in Scotland in 1881.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Later instances included games between British, French and Belgian teams in the 1920s, and a women's European Championship in 1957.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] During this time, women's football was often stifled or banned by male-dominated football federations in many countries.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] In Brazil, women's football was effectively illegal from 1941 until 1979.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] FIEFF organised a previous Women's World Cup in Italy in 1970, also won by Denmark.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The 1971 tournament featured five different qualifying groups, four in Europe and one in the Americas, where Argentina was the only team included in the initial draw.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Italy qualified for the main tournament against England and Austria, but England was later given a place in the finals after all teams from one of the European groups (Spain, Switzerland and West Germany) withdrew from the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Similarly, France qualified by defeating the Netherlands after the withdrawal of Czechoslovakia, and Denmark qualified by default after both Belgium and Sweden withdrew.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The Americas round was not played and Argentina qualified by default, as neither potential opponents, Chile and Costa Rica, fulfilled the necessary requirements for the matches to be played.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Some of the qualifiers and finals games were officially recognised – for example, the Italian Football Federation classes all of the 1971 Italy games as full internationals.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The match between France and the Netherlands in April 1971 was the first FIFA-recognised women's international match: it was played in Hazebrouck in front of 1,500 spectators.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] A protest was filled by the Dutch organization in charge of the team, to no avail.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Tournament sponsors Martini & Rossi paid for each team's travel, accommodation, and kits.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Goalposts were painted in pink hoops and stadium staff wore pink clothes, in order to try to appeal to women and families.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Ticket prices ranged from 30 pesos (£1.15) to 80 pesos (£3).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The tournament mascot was Xochitl, "a young girl in [a] football kit".
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The opening match of the finals, Mexico–Argentina (15 August) had a reported attendance of 100,000 at the Azteca Stadium.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] An estimated 80,000 people attended the Mexico–England group game.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The World Cup final, Mexico–Denmark, had an estimated attendance of 110,000, a world record for women's sport.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] This figure was reported both at the time and subsequently, and surviving footage supports the estimates.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The football record at the Azteca Stadium was three years earlier, 119,853 at the men's Mexico–Brazil match in July 1968.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The hosts Mexico qualified for the final after defeating Italy in the semifinals.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Two days before the final, the Mexican press noted the players for Mexico were unhappy they had not been receiving economic support for participating in the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The Mexican team threatened to skip the final but gave up their two million peso demand and the game went forward as scheduled.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Denmark won the tournament after beating Mexico 3–0 in the final, featuring a hat trick by 15-year-old Susanne Augustesen.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The victorious Danish team were treated to a celebratory reception at Copenhagen Town Hall upon their return from the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] However, due to the unofficial nature of the tournament, it is not recognised by the Danish Football Association.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] England's team included 13-year-old Leah Caleb, 14-year-old Gill Sayell, and 15-year-old Chris Lockwood; their captain was 19-year-old Carol Wilson and they were accompanied by referee Pat Dunn as a chaperone and trainer.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] 15-year-old Susanne Augustesen scored a hat-trick for Denmark as they beat Mexico 3–0 in the final.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Augustesen was honoured by the mayor of her hometown, Holbæk.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] 12 members of England's 14-woman squad reunited in June 2019 for the first time since the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] A match for fifth place was played between the two teams which did not advance to the semifinals.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was later followed by the series of Mundialito tournaments throughout the 1980s, mostly held in Italy, and FIFA's Women's Invitation Tournament in China in 1988 before the first FIFA Women's World Cup in China in 1991.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] In Mexico, *Tan cerca de las nubes*, directed by Manuel Cañibe, on that country's squad that participated in the 1970 cup in Italy, as well as the 1971 one.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] In Argentina, *México 71*, directed by Carolina Gil Solari and Carolina M.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] Fernández, on the Argentine squad's experiences during the cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1971-women-s-world-cup] In the UK, *Copa 71* (2023), directed by Rachel Ramsay and James Erskine.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The **1988 FIFA Women's Invitation Tournament**, or **International Women's Football Tournament**, was organised by FIFA in China from 1 to 12 June 1988.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The competition was a test to study if a global women's World Cup was feasible following the experience of non-FIFA invitational competitions such as the Mundialito (1981–88) and the Women's World Invitational Tournament (1978–87).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The competition was a success and on 30 June FIFA approved the establishment of an official World Cup for 1991, which would also be held in China.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] Twelve national teams took part in the competition – four from UEFA, three from AFC, two from CONCACAF and one from CONMEBOL, CAF and OFC.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] European champion Norway defeated Sweden 1–0 in the final to win the tournament, while Brazil clinched the bronze by beating the hosts in a penalty shootout.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] Australia, Canada, the Netherlands and the United States also reached the final stages.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The tournament took place in 4 cities in the province of Guangdong: Guangzhou, Foshan, Jiangmen and Panyu.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] 12 national teams participated in the tournament, all invited by FIFA.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The matches of China were held in Guangzhou.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The rest of the matches of this group were held in Foshan.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1988-fifa-women-s-invitation-tournament] The all star team was voted by the Chinese press.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] The **1991 FIFA Women's World Cup final** was an association football match that took place on 30 November 1991 at Tianhe Stadium in Guangzhou, China.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] It was played between Norway and the United States to determine the winner of the 1991 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] The United States beat Norway 2–1, with two goals from Michelle Akers-Stahl, to become winners of the first ever FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] The final was contested by Norway, who rebounded from a stunning 4–0 defeat by host nation China PR to qualify from their group.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] They then dispatched Italy and historic rivals Sweden in the knockout rounds to reach the final.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup-final] The other team in the final was the United States, who went undefeated throughout the competition, thrashing highly rated Germany 5–2 in the semi-final.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The **1991 FIFA Women's World Cup** was the first FIFA Women's World Cup, the world championship for women's national football teams.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It took place in Guangdong, China from 16 to 30 November 1991.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA, football's international governing body, selected China as host nation as Guangdong had hosted a prototype world championship three years earlier, the 1988 FIFA Women's Invitation Tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Matches were played in the provincial capital, Guangzhou, as well as in Foshan, Jiangmen and Zhongshan.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The competition was sponsored by Mars, Incorporated, maker of M&M's candy.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] With FIFA still reluctant to bestow their "World Cup" brand, the tournament was officially known as the **1st FIFA World Championship for Women's Football for the M&M's Cup**.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] It was won by the United States, whose captain April Heinrichs formed a forward line dubbed the "Triple-Edged Sword" with Carin Jennings and Michelle Akers.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Jennings was named player of the tournament while Akers's ten goals won the Golden Boot.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The United States defeated Norway 2–1 in the final in front of a crowd of 63,000 people at Guangzhou's Tianhe Stadium.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Total attendance for the tournament was 510,000, an average per match of 19,615.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] In the opening match at the same stadium, Norway was defeated 4–0 by hosts China.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Chinese defender Ma Li scored the first goal in Women's World Cup history, while goalkeeper Zhong Honglian, also of China, posted the first official clean sheet in the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The 12 qualified teams were divided into three groups of four (A to C).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The top two teams and the two best third-place finishers from the three groups advanced to the knockout round of eight teams.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For only this first edition of the Women's World Cup, all matches lasted only 80 minutes, instead of the typical 90, and two points were awarded for a win (both of which would change in 1995).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The 1991 Women's World Cup had twelve participating teams compete in the final tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Each of the six FIFA confederations had at least one representative.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For a list of the squads that contended for the final tournament, see *1991 FIFA Women's World Cup squads*.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] For the first time in FIFA competition, six female officials were included.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] All functioned as lineswomen, except for Cláudia Vasconcelos who took charge of the third place play-off; becoming the first woman to referee a match sanctioned by FIFA.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] FIFA's technical report demonstrates that, after the tournament, players and officials were undecided whether to persist with 80-minute matches, or to change to 90 minutes in line with men's football.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Opinion was also divided about the suitability of using a size five football.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Some teams reported difficulty in sourcing good quality equipment in the correct size.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The tournament was considered a major success in the quality of play and attendances at the games.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The perceived success of the tournament was a significant factor in the subsequent inclusion of women's football in the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Sue Lopez reported that although attendances were very high, many tickets were complimentary.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The "novelty factor" of women from foreign lands playing football also encouraged local people to attend.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The draw for the group stage was held on 14 September 1991 at the Tianhe Stadium in Guangzhou, China.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] The draw was part of a televised two-hour live show, featuring songs in both Chinese and English from the female singers Zhang Qiang (Beijing), Lin Ping (Guangzhou), Jenny Tseng (Hong Kong) and Irene Yeh (Taiwan).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Rules for classification: 1) Points; 2) Goal difference; 3) Goals scored.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] There were 99 goals scored in 26 matches, for an average of 3.81 goals per match.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Michelle Akers-Stahl of the United States won the Golden Boot award for scoring ten goals.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/1991-fifa-women-s-world-cup] Per statistical convention in football, matches decided in extra time are counted as wins and losses, while matches decided by penalty shoot-outs are counted as draws.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The **2019 FIFA Women's World Cup** was the eighth edition of the FIFA Women's World Cup, the quadrennial international Women's football championship contested by 24 women's national teams representing member associations of FIFA.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] It took place between 7 June and 7 July 2019, with 52 matches staged in nine cities in France, which was awarded the right to host the event in March 2015, the first time the country hosted the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The tournament was the first Women's World Cup to use the video assistant referee (VAR) system.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] This was the second and last edition with 24 teams before expanding to 32 teams for the 2023 tournament in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The United States entered the competition as defending champions after winning the 2015 edition and successfully defended their title, with a 2–0 victory over the Netherlands in the final.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] In doing so, they secured their record fourth title and became the second nation, after Germany, to have successfully retained the title.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Unlike Germany, however, this victory held a distinction as the United States won both 2015 and 2019 tournaments under one manager, Jill Ellis.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] It was the first time in 81 years since Vittorio Pozzo did so for the Italian men's team at the 1934 and 1938 FIFA World Cups.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The matches were broadcast globally and attracted a combined audience of 1.12 billion people.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] On 6 March 2014, FIFA announced that bidding had begun for the 2019 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Member associations interested in hosting the tournament had to submit a declaration of interest by 15 April 2014, and provide the complete set of bidding documents by 31 October 2014.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] As a principle, FIFA preferred the 2019 Women's World Cup and the 2018 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup to be hosted by the same member association, but reserved the right to award the hosting of the events separately.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Initially, five countries indicated interest in hosting the events: France, England, South Korea, New Zealand and South Africa.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Both England and New Zealand registered expressions of interest by the April 2014 deadline, but in June 2014 it was announced that each would no longer proceed.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] South Africa registered an expression of interest by the April 2014 deadline; but later decided to withdraw prior to the final October deadline.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Both Japan and Sweden had also expressed interest in bidding for the 2019 tournament, but Japan chose to focus on the 2019 Rugby World Cup and the 2020 Summer Olympics, whilst Sweden decided to focus on European U-17 competitions instead.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] France and South Korea made official bids for hosting the tournament by submitting their documents by 31 October 2014.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] On 19 March 2015, France officially won the bid to host the Women's World Cup and the U-20 Women's World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The decision came after a vote by the FIFA Executive Committee.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Upon the selection, France became the third European nation to host the Women's World Cup (following Sweden and Germany), and the fourth country to host both the men's and women's World Cup, having hosted the men's tournament in 1938 and 1998.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] By the time France hosted the women's World Cup, the country had also earlier hosted the UEFA Euro 2016, which served as a precursor for France's preparation to host this competition.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The slot allocation was approved by the FIFA Council on 13–14 October 2016.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The slots for each confederation are unchanged from those of the previous tournament except the slot for the hosts has been moved from CONCACAF (Canada) to UEFA (France).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Qualifying matches started on 3 April 2017 and ended on 1 December 2018.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] A total of 24 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Each team's FIFA Rankings in March 2019 are shown in parentheses.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Chile, Jamaica, Scotland and South Africa made their Women's World Cup debuts, while Italy took part in the event for the first time since 1999 and Argentina took part for the first time since 2007.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Brazil, Germany, Japan, Nigeria, Norway, Sweden and the United States qualified for their eighth World Cup, continuing their streak of qualifying for every World Cup held so far.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The final nine stadiums were chosen on 14 June 2017; Stade de la Beaujoire in Nantes, Stade Marcel-Picot in Nancy, and Stade de l'Abbé-Deschamps in Auxerre were cut.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The semi-finals and final were played at Parc Olympique Lyonnais in the Lyon suburb of Décines-Charpieu, with 58,000 capacity, while the opening match was played at Parc des Princes in Paris.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The 2019 tournament is the first under the 24-team format to be played without double-header fixtures.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] On 3 December 2018, FIFA announced the list of 27 referees and 48 assistant referees for the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] On 15 March 2019, the FIFA Council approved the use of the video assistant referee (VAR) system for the first time in a FIFA Women's World Cup tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The technology was previously deployed at the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The fifteen male VAR officials were announced by FIFA on 2 May 2019.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] French referee Stéphanie Frappart was in charge for the final between the United States and the Netherlands.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The draw for the final tournament was held on 8 December 2018, 18:00 CET (UTC+1), at the La Seine Musicale on the island of Île Seguin, Boulogne-Billancourt.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The 24 teams were drawn into six groups of four teams.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The 24 teams were allocated to four pots based on the FIFA Women's World Rankings released on 7 December 2018, with hosts France automatically placed in Pot 1 and position A1 in the draw.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Teams from Pot 1 were drawn first and assigned to Position 1.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] This was followed by Pot 2, Pot 3, and finally Pot 4, with each of these teams also drawn to one of the positions 2–4 within their group.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] No group could contain more than one team from each confederation apart from UEFA, which have nine teams, where three groups had to contain two UEFA teams.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Each team had to provide to FIFA a preliminary squad of between 23 and 50 players by 26 April 2019, which was not to be published.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] From the preliminary squad, each team had to name a final squad of 23 players (three of whom must be goalkeepers) by 24 May 2019.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Players in the final squad could be replaced by a player from the preliminary squad due to serious injury or illness up to 24 hours prior to kickoff of the team's first match.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The match schedule for the tournament was released on 8 February 2018.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Following the final draw, seven group stage kick-off times were adjusted by FIFA.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The top two teams of each group and the four best third-placed teams advanced to the round of 16.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The four best third-placed teams from the six groups advanced to the knockout stage along with the six group winners and six runners-up.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Rules for classification: 1) Points; 2) Goal difference; 3) Goals scored; 4) Fair play points; 5) Drawing of lots.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] In the knockout stage, if a match was level at the end of 90 minutes of normal playing time, extra time was played (two periods of 15 minutes each), where each team was allowed to make a fourth substitution.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] If the score was still level after extra time, the winners were determined by a penalty shoot-out.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The following awards were given at the conclusion of the tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The Golden Ball (best overall player), Golden Boot (top scorer) and Golden Glove (best goalkeeper) awards were sponsored by Adidas, while the Goal of the Tournament was sponsored by Hyundai Motor Company.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] FIFA.com shortlisted ten goals for users to vote on as the tournaments' best, with the poll closing on 17 July 2019.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The FIFA Technical Study Group announced a list of ten key players of the tournament who "dared to shine".
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] Prize money amounts were announced in October 2018.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] There were 146 goals scored in 52 matches, for an average of 2.81 goals per match.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The emblem and slogan were launched on 19 September 2017 at the Musée de l'Homme in Paris.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The emblem mimics the shape of the World Cup trophy and features a stylised football surrounded by eight decorative shards of light, symbolising the eighth edition of the Women's World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The World Cup's official English-language slogan is "Dare to Shine"; its French slogan is "Le moment de briller".
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] FIFA and the local organising committee sold tickets for the Women's World Cup beginning with a pre-sale of individual tickets in December 2018, single-city ticket packages in late 2018, and single-ticket sales for the general public beginning on 7 March 2019.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The online platform, hosted by AP2S, permitted fans to print their tickets beginning on 20 May 2019, which included seating assignments that had separated ticketholders who had purchased their tickets as a group or family.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] FIFA responded to online complaints by referring to a warning in the online system that had reminded purchasers that its tickets would not be guaranteed in the same areas, inciting further outrage, but allowed families with underage children to have adjacent seating.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The official mascot, "Ettie" (stylised in lowercase as "ettie) was unveiled on 12 May 2018 at the TF1 Group headquarters, and was broadcast on LCI.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] She made her first public appearance in Paris in front of the iconic Eiffel Tower.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] FIFA describe her as "a young chicken with a passion for life and football" and state that "she comes from a long line of "feathered mascots" and is the daughter of Footix, the Official Mascot of the 1998 FIFA World Cup in France".
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] FIFA sold the broadcasting rights for the World Cup to broadcasters through several companies.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] A total of 1.12 billion people globally watched the matches, and the final match attracted 82.18 million viewers, setting a new FIFA Women's World Cup record, surpassing the 2015 final.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p01] The 2019 tournament set several new viewership records for various countries.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] The World Cup was used by UEFA to qualify three teams for the 2020 Summer Olympic women's football tournament in Japan, with the three European teams with the best results (considering only the round they reach) qualifying.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] If teams in contention for Olympic spots were eliminated in the same round, a maximum of four teams (determined by group stage results if necessary) would advance to play-offs in early 2020 to decide the remaining spot(s).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] However, this scenario did not happen for this tournament.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] Scotland also qualified for the World Cup but, under the agreement whereby the highest ranked home nation was nominated to compete for the purposes of Olympic qualification, their performance would not be taken into account.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] In effect, therefore, eight European teams competed for three qualification places during the World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] The United States' win over France in the quarter-finals guaranteed that the three remaining semi-finalists, all from UEFA, qualified for the Olympics.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] The final's scheduling on 7 July led to a degree of criticism among supporters of women's football, as two continental men's tournament finals were held on the same day—the Copa América in Rio de Janeiro and the CONCACAF Gold Cup in Chicago.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] CONCACAF president Victor Montagliani described the scheduling as "a mistake", but claimed the error could not be reversed for logistical reasons.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] The lack of outdoor advertising across Paris, except for the Parc des Princes stadium and the temporary World Cup museum at Châtelet, was also criticised.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] The Women's World Cup was the first major competition to use the updated Laws of the Game approved by the International Football Association Board (IFAB), which came into effect on 1 June 2019.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] Among the changes, the more severe punishment of goalkeeper encroachment during penalty kicks—including retakes after a video assistant referee review—gained the most attention and caused several successful saves to be disallowed in the group stage.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] The use of the Women's World Cup as a "guinea pig" for the new changes to the rules was also criticised by some footballers and coaches for being potentially sexist, as several concurrent men's continental competitions had not implemented them.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] Pierluigi Collina, head of referees for FIFA, denied the claim, stating that it had long been customary for rule changes to be introduced in June, before major tournaments.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] Following widespread criticism and a request from FIFA, the IFAB issued a temporary dispensation to waive the requirement to show goalkeepers a yellow card for stepping off the line during a penalty shootout during the knockout stage of the Women's World Cup.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] The round of 16 fixture between England and Cameroon was marred by misbehaviour of some Cameroonian players, who refused to kick off for several minutes after the second English goal, deliberately fouled several players, and argued with the referee while huddling around her.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] Cameroonian defender Augustine Ejangue was also seen on camera spitting at English winger Toni Duggan after conceding an indirect free kick in the penalty area, from which England later scored.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] After the match, England manager Phil Neville said it "didn't feel like football" and that he was "completely and utterly ashamed of the opposition".
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] The Confederation of African Football (CAF) condemned some of the players' actions, while also criticising the refereeing.
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] Cameroon felt three crucial decisions were unjust, two of which involved the video assistant referee (VAR).
[src:2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup/2019-fifa-women-s-world-cup-p02] FIFA announced that it would investigate the match.
